Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates a race condition bug in a visual counter widget. The file includes:

- **Buggy Version**: A simple counter that uses `setTimeout` for asynchronous updates. When you rapidly click the "Increment" button, multiple updates overlap, leading to race conditions. This means the counter may not reflect the correct value because multiple operations read the same initial value of the shared variable, modify it, and write back, overwriting each other's changes.

- **Corrected Version**: A counter that uses a queue to process updates sequentially. This ensures that even if clicks happen rapidly, the updates are handled one at a time, preventing race conditions.

- **Side-by-Side Layout**: The two versions are displayed in separate columns for easy comparison.

- **Explanation**: Below each version, there's a clear, visible explanation of the issue and the fix.

You can save this as an `.html` file (e.g., `race_condition_demo.html`) and open it in a web browser to interact with it. Try clicking the buttons rapidly to see the buggy behavior in action!

Here's the full HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Race Condition Demo</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .container {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-around;
        }
        .section {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            padding: 20px;
            width: 45%;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .explanation {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-style: italic;
            color: #555;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Race Condition Demonstration</h1>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Buggy Version</h2>
            <p>Count: <span id="buggyCount">0</span></p>
            <button id="buggyButton">Increment (Buggy)</button>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p><strong>Explanation of the Bug:</strong> In this version, each button click schedules an asynchronous update using <code>setTimeout</code>. If you click the button rapidly, multiple updates overlap. They all read the current value of the shared <code>buggyCount</code> variable at the same time, add 1 to their individual copies, and then write back. This causes race conditions, where later updates overwrite earlier ones, resulting in the displayed count being lower than expected (e.g., after 5 rapid clicks, you might see 3 instead of 5).</p>
                <p><strong>Why it happens:</strong> The operations are not atomic or synchronized, so the shared state is accessed concurrently without protection.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Corrected Version</h2>
            <p>Count: <span id="correctedCount">0</span></p>
            <button id="correctedButton">Increment (Corrected)</button>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p><strong>Explanation of the Fix:</strong> This version uses a queue to process updates sequentially. Each button click adds an increment task to the queue, and the queue ensures that tasks are executed one at a time. Even with rapid clicks, the updates wait for the previous one to finish before proceeding, so the shared <code>correctedCount</code> variable is always updated correctly.</p>
                <p><strong>How it resolves the issue:</strong> By enforcing a sequence (using a queue and callbacks), we prevent overlapping access to the shared state, making the operations effectively atomic in this context. After rapid clicks, the count will accurately reflect the total number of clicks.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Buggy Version Implementation
        let buggyCount = 0;  // Shared counter variable

        function buggyIncrement() {
            setTimeout(() => {
                // Read the current value
                let current = buggyCount;
                // Simulate a delay in modification (though it's instant here)
                buggyCount = current + 1;  // Modify and write back
                updateBuggyDisplay();  // Update the display
            }, 0);  // Asynchronous delay
        }

        function updateBuggyDisplay() {
            document.getElementById('buggyCount').textContent = buggyCount;
        }

        // Add event listener for buggy button
        document.getElementById('buggyButton').addEventListener('click', buggyIncrement);

        // Corrected Version Implementation
        let correctedCount = 0;  // Shared counter variable
        let queue = [];  // Queue to hold tasks

        function enqueue(task) {
            queue.push(task);
            if (queue.length === 1) {  // If queue was empty, start processing
                processQueue();
            }
        }

        function processQueue() {
            if (queue.length > 0) {
                const task = queue[0];  // Get the first task
                task(() => {  // Execute the task with a callback
                    queue.shift();  // Remove the completed task
                    processQueue();  // Process the next one
                });
            }
        }

        function correctedIncrement() {
            enqueue(callback => {
                // Perform the increment
                correctedCount = correctedCount + 1;
                updateCorrectedDisplay();
                // After the task is done, call the callback to continue
                setTimeout(callback, 0);  // Keep it asynchronous but sequential
            });
        }

        function updateCorrectedDisplay() {
            document.getElementById('correctedCount').textContent = correctedCount;
        }

        // Add event listener for corrected button
        document.getElementById('correctedButton').addEventListener('click', correctedIncrement);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use This Demo:
1. Open the file in a web browser.
2. Click the "Increment (Buggy)" button a few times slowly – it should work fine.
3. Now, click it rapidly (e.g., 5-10 times quickly). You'll likely see the count lag behind or show an incorrect value due to the race condition.
4. Switch to the "Increment (Corrected)" button and repeat the rapid clicks. The count should always be accurate.

