Below is a single, self-contained HTML file that demonstrates a race condition bug in a visual counter widget. The file includes:

- **Two side-by-side counter widgets**: 
  - The **buggy version** uses asynchronous updates with `setTimeout`, which can lead to race conditions when the button is clicked rapidly. This happens because multiple updates might overlap, reading and writing to the shared count variable at the same time, resulting in incorrect values (e.g., the count might increment less than expected).
  - The **corrected version** uses a promise-based queue to serialize the updates, ensuring that each update waits for the previous one to finish, thus preventing race conditions.

- **Visible explanations**: I've included clear, inline explanations in the HTML to describe the race condition and how it's fixed. These are displayed as paragraphs below each counter for easy reference.

To see the bug in action:
- Open this HTML file in a web browser.
- Rapidly click the button in the buggy version (e.g., 5-10 times in quick succession). You'll notice the displayed count might not match the number of clicks (e.g., if you click 5 times, it might show 3 or 4).
- Compare this to the corrected version, where the count should always accurately reflect the number of clicks, even with rapid clicking.

Here's the complete HTML file. You can copy and paste it into a text editor, save it as `race_condition_demo.html`, and open it in your browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Race Condition Demo in Counter Widget</title>
    <style>
        /* Basic styling for layout and visuals */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }

        #demo {
            display: flex;
            gap: 40px; /* Space between the two sections */
            justify-content: center;
        }

        #buggy, #corrected {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            width: 45%; /* Make them side by side */
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            font-size: 16px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }

        h2 {
            color: #333;
        }

        .explanation {
            font-style: italic;
            color: #666;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Race Condition Demo in a Counter Widget</h1>

    <div id="explanation">
        <p><strong>Overall Explanation:</strong> This demo shows a simple counter widget with two versions. In both, clicking the button schedules an asynchronous update using <code>setTimeout</code> to increment a shared count variable. However:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Race Condition in the Buggy Version:</strong> When you click the button rapidly, multiple updates overlap. Each update reads the current count, modifies it (adds 1), and writes it back. If two or more updates happen concurrently (e.g., both read the count as 0 before either writes), they might overwrite each other's changes, leading to lost increments. For example, if the count is 0 and you click twice quickly, both updates might read 0, then both write 1, resulting in a final count of 1 instead of 2. This is a classic race condition because the operations are not atomic or synchronized.</li>
            <li><strong>How the Fix Works in the Corrected Version:</strong> To resolve this, we use a promise-based queue to serialize the updates. Each click adds its update to a chain of promises, ensuring that the next update only starts after the previous one finishes. This prevents overlapping reads and writes, making the counter accurate even under rapid clicks.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Try clicking the buttons rapidly to observe the difference!</p>
    </div>

    <div id="demo">
        <div id="buggy">
            <h2>Buggy Version (Race Condition Demonstrated)</h2>
            <p>Click the button below rapidly (e.g., 5-10 times quickly). The count may not increment correctly due to overlapping asynchronous updates.</p>
            <button id="buggyButton">Increment Buggy Counter</button>
            <p>Count: <span id="buggyCount">0</span></p>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p><strong>Why the Bug Occurs:</strong> Each click schedules a <code>setTimeout</code> that reads, modifies, and writes the count asynchronously. If clicks overlap, multiple timeouts might execute out of order or simultaneously in the event loop, causing some increments to be lost. For instance, if two clicks happen before the first update finishes, both may read the same initial value, leading to incorrect results.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="corrected">
            <h2>Corrected Version (Race Condition Fixed)</h2>
            <p>Click the button below rapidly. The count should always be accurate because updates are properly sequenced.</p>
            <button id="correctedButton">Increment Corrected Counter</button>
            <p>Count: <span id="correctedCount">0</span></p>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p><strong>How the Fix Resolves It:</strong> This version uses a promise chain to queue updates. Each click waits for the previous update to complete before proceeding, ensuring that reads and writes to the count are not interleaved. Even though <code>setTimeout</code> is still used for asynchronous behavior, the promise ensures atomicity, preventing lost increments.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Buggy counter variables and logic
        let buggyCount = 0;
        const buggySpan = document.getElementById('buggyCount');
        const buggyButton = document.getElementById('buggyButton');

        buggyButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            setTimeout(() => {
                // Read the current count
                let temp = buggyCount;  // Potential race: If another update reads here, it might get the same value
                // Modify the count
                temp = temp + 1;
                // Write the updated count
                buggyCount = temp;
                // Update the display
                buggySpan.textContent = buggyCount;
            }, 0);  // Asynchronous delay to simulate potential overlap
        });

        // Corrected counter variables and logic
        let correctedCount = 0;
        let incrementQueue = Promise.resolve();  // Start with a resolved promise for chaining
        const correctedSpan = document.getElementById('correctedCount');
        const correctedButton = document.getElementById('correctedButton');

        correctedButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
            incrementQueue = incrementQueue.then(() => {
                return new Promise(resolve => {
                    setTimeout(() => {
                        // Read and modify the count
                        correctedCount = correctedCount + 1;  // This is now safe due to the queue
                        // Update the display
                        correctedSpan.textContent = correctedCount;
                        resolve();  // Resolve the promise to allow the next update
                    }, 0);  // Still asynchronous, but sequenced
                });
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

