    <button id="buggy-button">Increment Buggy</button>
    <p class="explanation">
      This version demonstrates a race condition. When you rapidly click the button, multiple asynchronous updates (using setTimeout) overlap. Each click reads the current count, schedules an increment after a delay, and writes back the new value. If clicks happen quickly, later updates might read the same initial value, leading to lost updates (e.g., the count might increment less than the number of clicks). This occurs because JavaScript's single-threaded event loop doesn't guarantee the order of asynchronous operations, allowing them to interfere with each other.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Corrected Counter</h2>
    <p>Count: <span id="corrected-count">0</span></p>
    <button id="corrected-button">Increment Corrected</button>
